# **MORALE** {#morale}

![][image15]

This section describes rules relative to unit morale and associated impacts to allowable actions.

### Morale Tests

Morale tests are a category of tests; a “Morale Test” does not have a specific outcome.  When a rule affects Morale Tests it affects the following tests:

* **Break Tests:** Taken at the end of a fight by units that have lost the fight to determine if they become **BROKEN**.  
* **Casualty Tests:** Taken at the end of a Shooting Phase by units who have taken casualties of 25% or more of their strength to determine if they become **BROKEN**.  
* **Pinning Tests:** A test to see if a Unit becomes **PINNED** as a result of being fired upon.  
* **Regroup Tests:** A test taken at the beginning of the controlling player’s turn to determine if **BROKEN** units remain **BROKEN**.

### Broken Units {#broken-units}

Units become **BROKEN** due to failing a break test or casualty test (or due to another cause), and suffer the following: 

* Unengaged broken units must perform a **FALL BACK MOVE** at the start of their turn.  
* **SHOOTING WHEN BROKEN**: Broken units may shoot during their own shooting phase, but count as having moved (given they will have performed a fall back move).  
* Broken units may NOT go onto overwatch or perform reactions (Take Cover\!, Return Fire\!, Stand & Shoot\!)  
* **CHARGING BROKEN UNITS:** If an unengaged broken unit is charged by an enemy unit, it must immediately test to regroup.  If the regroup test **passes**, the unit immediately regroups (see [REGROUPING](#regrouping)). If the test **fails** the unit strikes at Initiative 1 for the current assault phase and loses the benefits of cover.  
* **BROKEN UNITS & PINNING**: Units that are broken and become pinned, or that are pinned and become broken will fallback 2D6”on their movement phase (they are not limited to the D3” move of PINNING) and also suffer the other effects of pinning (see [PINNING](#pinning)).

### Regrouping {#regrouping}

Units that are broken may attempt to **REGROUP** at the **start of the turn** by passing a REGROUP test.

* **REGROUP TEST:** Units attempting to regroup must meet the following conditions to be able to take the test:  
  * There must be at least one model left alive in the unit.  
  * It may not be engaged or within 1” of an enemy unit.  
  * All models in the unit must be within coherency distance.  
* A regroup test is a leadership test using the model's highest applicable leadership value. The test is subject to the following modifiers;  
  * \-1 if the unit is below **HALF-STRENGTH** (i.e. less than 50% of starting strength)  
  * \-1 if the unit is not in coherency  
* **IF PASSED:** If the test is passed, the unit may not take a normal or advance move, but may instead be moved up to D3” during their movement phase. The unit may shoot, but counts as having moved regardless of how far it moves. The unit may charge as normal.  
* **IF FAILED**: If the test is failed, the unit remains broken and must immediately make a **FALL BACK MOVE**.  The unit may attempt to regroup again on a subsequent turn if eligible to do so.

### Falling Back {#falling-back}

When a unit is instructed to make a **FALL BACK MOVE**, the following rules apply:

* **DISTANCE & DIRECTION:** Units that fall back move 2D6” towards the nearest table edge in their deployment zone **and** must end their move further away from any enemy models than they were before making the fall back move to the extent possible.  
  * Models may move around impassable terrain or other obstructions (e.g. enemy models or impassable terrain) following the shortest distance possible, starting with the model closest to the applicable table edge before moving.  
  * Fallback moves are not affected by difficult terrain but must test for dangerous terrain if normally required to do so.   
  * Falling back models may move through their own non-vehicle units, provided they do not end their move on top of another model or out of coherency. *This is an exception to the normal rules of not being able to move through other models.*  
  * Some types of models fall back 3D6” instead of the normal fall back move.  These types include: **JUMP INFANTRY, BIKES, JETBIKES, CAVALRY, BEAST,** and **FLYING CREATURES**  
* **TRAPPED:** If a unit cannot perform its full fall back due to being blocked by nearby enemy models, vehicles of either player, or impassable terrain, the unit must move as far as possible away from enemy models and then automatically becomes **PINNED** and remains broken (if already broken).  
* **UNITS ENTERING FROM OUTSIDE DEPLOYMENT ZONES:** Units which entered play from outside of their player’s deployment zone must fall back towards the nearest table edge while moving further away from enemy models than they were before the fall back move.  
* **REACHING THE TABLE EDGE:** If a falling back unit would end up moving one or more models off a table edge, move the unit up to the edge of the table as far as possible and stop. At the start of the controlling players next turn, they make one final test to **REGROUP**. If it fails, the unit is removed from play and destroyed.


### Insane Heroism

* Anytime a morale test is made (i.e. Break, Casualty, Pinning, or Regroup Test), if double 1’s are rolled on the 2D6 the unit benefits from insane heroism.  Until the end of its next turn, the unit automatically passes all morale tests.
